ing the age of the Crusades. It examines the long and short-term impact of Islamic authority and culture on these regions and how they later fell into the hands of European rulers, explaining how the Norman conquest of Sicily came to import radically different dynamics to the central Mediterranean. The change of ruling elites left a majority Muslim population under Christian rule, but the Sicilian kings also adopted and adapted political ideologies from south Mediterranean regimes while absorbing cultural influences from the diverse peoples over whom they ruled. This work provides an engaging, expert and wide-ranging introduction to the subject and offers fresh and clear insights into the political, religious, social, economic and cultural evolution of Europe and the Islamic world. Key FeaturesA welcome introduction a field where very little has been writtenExplores the formation of lasting Muslim-Christian frontiers in medieval EuropeCovers issues including Muslim-Christian relations, conquest, colonisation, conflict and acculturation, and the transmission and exchange of ideas from east to west"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxIslam. 0aIslamxRelationsxChristianity. 0aMuslimsxHistoryxTo 1500xItalyxSicily. 0aMuslimsxHistoryxTo 1500xItaly. 0aMuslimszItalyxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMuslimszItalyzSicilyxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074862911440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748629114423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748629114/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL